barcode identical to R. perplana collected in BC.

David Ruiter: "perplana/vuzana - all three taxa in the R.angelita group (I don't think R. newelli belongs there but I don't have any) are very similar and folks have struggled throughout the western range. Angelita occurs down through the eastern Rockies (there are records of angelita from MN and NH) while all three are reported together in the coastal range. They could easily all be the same, or just two with perplana being a syn of vuzana. The females of angelita and vuzana are only slightly different. I have a "perplana" male and female from the collection I sent you so they are clearing now and I will see if I can see anything different in the "perplana" female. The perplana description indicates all three taxa were collected at the same locality and there should be more perplana types at the INHS (Ross & Spencer 1952). Maybe you could get a part from one of Ross's perplana types to check.-Jul 13, 2010.

Dave Ruiter: "perplana/vuzana - all three taxa in the R.angelita group (I don't think R. newelli belongs there but I don't have any) are very similar and folks have struggled throughout the western range. Angelita occurs down through the eastern Rockies (there are records of angelita from MN and NH) while all three are reported together in the coastal range. They could easily all be the same, or just two with perplana being a syn of vuzana. The females of angelita and vuzana are only slightly different. I have a "perplana" male and female from the collection I sent you so they are clearing now and I will see if I can see anything different in the "perplana" female. The perplana description indicates all three taxa were collected at the same locality and there should be more perplana types at the INHS (Ross & Spencer 1952). Maybe you could get a part from one of Ross's perplana types to check.-Jul 13, 2010

Xin Zhou note: this larval specimen was identified as R. caladon and was published in Zhou et al. 2011 as such. Jason Robonson later possitively associated this morph with R. appalachia. The ID therefore is being updated. - May 4, 2011.

Jason Robinson: "Hey y'all thought I'd share what I recently learned. We had some Rhyacophila nigrita group larvae from Guilford Co NC, which is a bit outside of the range and habitat that the members of this species group typically occupy, at least in my conception of the group. We sequenced one of these larvae (PKCAD292-07) and the barcode identified as Rhyacophila celadon. We knew that the bar code identification had failed with this group in other instances and in this case we were positive that the larvae did not possess the diagnostic characters that separate R celadon from the other species in the complex. So, this spring I managed to associate the things and what we have is Rhyacophila appalachia. Males and females are typical. I was very excited about this record, I just knew it would be a new one but this is still a pretty great record. Thought I'd share! Chuck this might be worth adding to the list for GUCO. Xin I didn't change the entries in the BOLD database but I will if necessary. Dr Morse thought you might be interested since we had just discussed this and also the likelihood that there may be other isolated populations of R nigrita group species down in the piedmont. I can't see NCDWQ sampling this little spit of water so they might not be picking them up. " - May 2, 2011.

David Ruiter: "perplana/vuzana - all three taxa in the R.angelita group (I don't think R. newelli belongs there but I don't have any) are very similar and folks have struggled throughout the western range. Angelita occurs down through the eastern Rockies (there are records of angelita from MN and NH) while all three are reported together in the coastal range. They could easily all be the same, or just two with perplana being a syn of vuzana. The females of angelita and vuzana are only slightly different. I have a "perplana" male and female from the collection I sent you so they are clearing now and I will see if I can see anything different in the "perplana" female. The perplana description indicates all three taxa were collected at the same locality and there should be more perplana types at the INHS (Ross & Spencer 1952). Maybe you could get a part from one of Ross's perplana types to check.-Jul 13, 2010.

OrigID=R. vuzana. Re-evaluated by Ollie: "male, perplana, but perplana and vuzana may be synonyms." - Aug 2, 2010.

notes:
barcode identical to R. perplana collected in BC.

David Ruiter: "perplana/vuzana - all three taxa in the R.angelita group (I don't think R. newelli belongs there but I don't have any) are very similar and folks have struggled throughout the western range. Angelita occurs down through the eastern Rockies (there are records of angelita from MN and NH) while all three are reported together in the coastal range. They could easily all be the same, or just two with perplana being a syn of vuzana. The females of angelita and vuzana are only slightly different. I have a "perplana" male and female from the collection I sent you so they are clearing now and I will see if I can see anything different in the "perplana" female. The perplana description indicates all three taxa were collected at the same locality and there should be more perplana types at the INHS (Ross & Spencer 1952). Maybe you could get a part from one of Ross's perplana types to check.-Jul 13, 2010.

OrigID=R. vuzana. Re-evaluated by Ollie: "male, perplana, but perplana and vuzana may be synonyms." - Aug 2, 2010.
